<p><b>Christian meditation</b> is <a href="/wiki/Meditation" title="Meditation">meditation</a> in a <a href="/wiki/Christian" title="Christian">Christian</a> context. The word meditation has come to have two different meanings: (1) continued, intent, focused thought; and (2) a state of quiet, intentionally unfocused, "contentless" awareness. This double meaning has contributed to misunderstanding and disagreement about the nature, role, and even the appropriateness of Christian meditation. Traditionally, the word meditation (<i>meditatio</i>) had the first meaning, and another word, <a href="/wiki/Contemplation" title="Contemplation">contemplation</a> (<i>contemplatio</i>) was used for the second.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since October 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
